title: For Sale:  SPR Mk12 Mod 0 6.8spc
postcontent:
A clone of the original SPR Mk12 Mod 0 in 6.8spc

The United States Navy Mark 12 Mod 0/1 Special Purpose Rifle (SPR) is a rifle in service with United States Special Operations Forces in Operation Enduring Freedom and previously in Operation Iraqi Freedom. SPR initially stood for Special Purpose Receiver, but that nomenclature has been replaced as the weapon became a stand-alone weapons system, and not just an add-on upper receiver assembly (part of the proposed SOPMOD upgrades). The SPR was eventually type classified by the U.S. Navy as the Mk 12. Note that the weapon was developed by a Navy office (Naval Surface Warfare Center Crane Division) for SOCOM units, not for use by units that fall under the conventional US Navy.

For more detailed information go to Wikipedia and enter> Mk 12 Special Purpose Rifle.

I can ship, also I will detach the upper from the lower and sell separate. This was a very exhausting clone to build. Nothing but the best parts currently used by the U.S. Armed Forces was put into making this, Knights Armament, Colt, A.R.M.S., Harris Bipod, KMW, Tool Craft, Precision Reflex Inc., Douglas Barrels, and Sierra Precision. Good luck trying to track these parts down in todays market. 

The price reflects my time and energy finding these parts and putting this excellant rifle together. The upper was put together by PRI, and the lower by a Knights Armament armorer.

title: For Sale:  SPR Mk12 Mod 0 6.8spc
postcontent:
A clone of the original SPR Mk12 Mod 0 in 6.8spc.

The United States Navy Mark 12 Mod 0/1 Special Purpose Rifle (SPR) is a rifle in service with United States Special Operations Forces in Operation Enduring Freedom and previously in Operation Iraqi Freedom. SPR initially stood for Special Purpose Receiver, but that nomenclature has been replaced as the weapon became a stand-alone weapons system, and not just an add-on upper receiver assembly (part of the proposed SOPMOD upgrades). The SPR was eventually type classified by the U.S. Navy as the Mk 12. Note that the weapon was developed by a Navy office (Naval Surface Warfare Center Crane Division) for SOCOM units, not for use by units that fall under the conventional US Navy.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Colt Mustang .380ACP, Series 80 w/ mags, holsters, & ammo
postcontent:
Up for sale is my beloved Colt Mustang, Series 80, made in 1986, chambered in .380ACP.  This gun was made before Colt stopped making the Mustang in the 90's, before the production of the current Pocketlite, aluminum framed Mustangs.  This is a steel framed pistol with the Colt-Guard electroless-nickle finish, which is a very durable, corrosion resistant finish.  I replaced the original, plastic factory trigger with a steel trigger.  This gun also has a full length guide rod from Wolfe.  

This little gun is a great shooter, and would make an excellent carry gun.  I am extremely accurate with this little pistol, thanks in part to the extremely clean, crisp trigger.  In fact, Sig patterned the P238 & P938 on this pistol.

I am selling this gun with some extras as a package deal.  You will get:

2 original Colt magazines (7 round, flush fit)
2 additional flush fit magazines (1 Sig, 1 Metalform)
3 extended magazines (8 round, 2 aftermarket, 1 Sig)
1 leather back pocket holster
1 Desantis Superfly holster (for pocket or IWB carry)
44 rounds of Hornady self defense JHP ammo

I am asking $850 for this package.

I also have quite a bit of .380ACP brass cased FMJ practice ammo available in another ad.  $20/box of 50 rounds, up to 25 boxes available.  Buy all the ammo and the pistol for $1200.

title: For Sale:  1987 Honda Fourtrax TRX250X
postcontent:
Straight from the first original line-up of Honda to replace the once legal then outlawed all-terrain 3-wheeler, the Fourtrax series of quad runners had some mighty big trail shoes to fill, but they did not disappoint, and this bad-boy trail racer was no exception.  It might be “just” a 250cc, but this quad is NOT for the kids.  The top end of the motor has been bored for that extra “pop” in speed, not that it needed it, because it still jumps off the starting line better than most other makes ever did new, and will buck off an over-confidently careless rider as easily as an unseasoned one.

Like too many of my other toys, this one just doesn’t get used any more because of kids and time schedules (and honestly, I just don’t bounce as well as I used to either), so I need to find it a good home.  This machine has been ridden hard, but has also been maintained with genuine Honda OEM mechanical parts, and regular oil and filter changes.  It has been flipped, but it has never been sunk in the mud or wrecked.  The frame is in perfect condition, and there are no fluid leaks from the motor or mechanics.

In the last 300 miles of riding and in addition to the minor maintenance, it has also had: a carburetor rebuild and tank flush (but the half tank of gas in it needs to be drained and fresh put in, it’s just old); new drive sprocket and cover, drive chain, tension pad and rear axle sprocket replacement; the rear end was rebuilt with fresh bearings, grease and seals; a new skid plate and rear brake disc and pads were installed; the mono-shock was replaced; the front wheel bearings were cleaned and freshly repacked; the brake fluid was drained and fresh fluid put in; new rear aftermarket body plastic was installed; rear and then front racks were added.

In addition, I have the stuff but haven’t gotten around to installing yet:  a rear tow hitch; a new front light/ignition key housing; a new control switch cluster; new vinyl for the seat.  I am also including the helmet with 3/4 flip visor, gas tank saddlebags, owners’ service manual, a spare grip, and some older parts like an air filter for high-dust riding, the last drive chain for spare links, and some other miscellaneous items.

I will accept cash or certified cashier’s check; absolutely no personal checks.  I’m asking $1,800 for this quad runner.  That may seem a bit much for the year, but I know how well it performs compared to other newer, supposedly performance-modified machines, and I know that it has been maintained better than 95% of other used machines.  You will have a better chance of negotiating price if you have cash, although I may be interested in a partial trade, if you have an AR platform NIB tactical rifle that employs gas-piston cycling or an AK or SK platform tactical rifle that is either NIB or LNIB with very low rounds through it.  I also might consider decent LNIB tactical shotguns in 12ga. or .410, or NIB 1911 semi-auto models in .45 or .50 with full-length or longer barrels.  I’ll have a lot more interest in trading for something out of the ordinary than something commonplace.

title: For Sale:  Sig Sauer P938 MGE12 3" 9mm
postcontent: The Sig Sauer P938 has been described as the P238’s bigger brother. Chambered in 9mm, the gun does resemble its .380 counterpart. The two pistols also share many of the same features. The P938 is a single action pistol in a lightweight alloy-frame that can be carried “cocked an locked” in a manner similar to the 1911 handguns. It has a crisp trigger that makes for a more pleasurable shooting experience than most double-action-only subcompact pistols. The Sig Sauer P938 frame is short, where the magazine is single-stack, allowing for a much thinner profile than a double-stack sub- compact pistol. The P938 is only 1.1” at the widest point. Reduced thickness comes at the cost in capacity, however, as the P938 mags only hold six rounds. The Sig Sauer P938 is equipped with tritium night sights, in transverse dovetails, and offer the standard three-dot combat sight setup. The safety is ambidextrous thumb activated with a positive detent (a spring and plunger in the frame) and works positively from both sides. Unloaded, the Sig Sauer P938 only weighs 16 ounces. Considering the SIG has an alloy frame, instead of a polymer frame, that is fairly impressive. Sig Sauer P938 accuracy is excellent for a micro compact pistol.

title: For Sale:  AR-15 buyer beware / help for prospective buyers
postcontent:
Gents - beware when making a purchase for a high end AR ( the feeding frenzy is over ) 
Many people are cautious about revealing to many details 
An AD may read " I have a Wilson " or I have a "Daniel defense" when what they have is only a few brand name parts and accessories - NOT a true high end rifle 

ALL brand name companies are very proud of their brand and will "laser etch / engrave" or stamp their logo on any major component .
Don't get suckered into over paying for cheap junk passed off a "high end" 


The heart of any AR-15  boils down to the following parts 
1. Upper and lower receiver 
2. Bolt carrier group 
3. Barrel 
The rest is not that critical to accuracy and durability 

I can build a quality AR , but I prefer to buy only factory built ARs that have a lifetime / transferable warranty - do your homework 

Bubba's house of ARs - may slap together a $99 upper , a $69 lower , $50 lower part kit , $99 BCG , $129 barrel then wrap the turd up in magpul , or Daniel defense rails , Wilson combat rail and stock and try to sell it for $1500.00 when he has about $750 invested .

I built my first home project AR for about $700
